#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:4
msgid "function - create a function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:7
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:9
msgid "function NAME [OPTIONS]; BODY; end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:15
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:17
msgid "``function`` creates a new function *NAME* with the body *BODY*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:19
msgid ""
"A function is a list of commands that will be executed when the name of the "
"function is given as a command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:21
msgid "The following options are available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:23
msgid "**-a** *NAMES* or **--argument-names** *NAMES*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:24
msgid ""
"Assigns the value of successive command-line arguments to the names given in "
"*NAMES*. These are the same arguments given in :envvar:`argv`, and are still "
"available there. See also :ref:`Argument Handling <variables-argv>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:26
msgid "**-d** *DESCRIPTION* or **--description** *DESCRIPTION*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:27
msgid ""
"A description of what the function does, suitable as a completion "
"description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:29
msgid "**-w** *WRAPPED_COMMAND* or **--wraps** *WRAPPED_COMMAND*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:30
msgid ""
"Inherit completions from the given *WRAPPED_COMMAND*. See the documentation "
"for :doc:`complete <complete>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:32
msgid "**-e** *EVENT_NAME* or **--on-event** *EVENT_NAME*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:33
msgid ""
"Run this function when the specified named event is emitted. Fish internally "
"generates named events, for example, when showing the prompt. Custom events "
"can be emitted using the :doc:`emit <emit>` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:35
msgid "**-v** *VARIABLE_NAME* or **--on-variable** *VARIABLE_NAME*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:36
msgid ""
"Run this function when the variable *VARIABLE_NAME* changes value. Note "
"that :program:`fish` makes no guarantees on any particular timing or even "
"that the function will be run for every single ``set``. Rather it will be "
"run when the variable has been set at least once, possibly skipping some "
"values or being run when the variable has been set to the same value (except "
"for universal variables set in other shells - only changes in the value will "
"be picked up for those)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:38
msgid "**-j** *PID* or **--on-job-exit** *PID*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:39
msgid ""
"Run this function when the job containing a child process with the given "
"process identifier *PID* exits. Instead of a PID, the string 'caller' can be "
"specified. This is only allowed when in a command substitution, and will "
"result in the handler being triggered by the exit of the job which created "
"this command substitution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:41
msgid "**-p** *PID* or **--on-process-exit** *PID*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:42
msgid ""
"Run this function when the fish child process with process ID PID exits. "
"Instead of a PID, for backward compatibility, \"``%self``\" can be specified "
"as an alias for ``$fish_pid``, and the function will be run when the current "
"fish instance exits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:44
msgid "**-s** *SIGSPEC* or **--on-signal** *SIGSPEC*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:45
msgid ""
"Run this function when the signal ``SIGSPEC`` is delivered. ``SIGSPEC`` can "
"be a signal number, or the signal name, such as ``SIGHUP`` (or just "
"``HUP``). Note that the signal must have been delivered to :program:`fish`; "
"for example, :kbd:`Ctrl-C` sends ``SIGINT`` to the foreground process group, "
"which will not be :program:`fish` if you are running another command at the "
"time. Observing a signal will prevent fish from exiting in response to that "
"signal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:47
msgid "**-S** or **--no-scope-shadowing**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:48
msgid ""
"Allows the function to access the variables of calling functions. Normally, "
"any variables inside the function that have the same name as variables from "
"the calling function are \"shadowed\", and their contents are independent of "
"the calling function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:50
msgid ""
"It's important to note that this does not capture referenced variables or "
"the scope at the time of function declaration! At this time, fish does not "
"have any concept of closures, and variable lifetimes are never extended. In "
"other words, by using **--no-scope-shadowing** the scope of the function "
"each time it is run is shared with the scope it was *called* from rather "
"than the scope it was *defined* in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:52
msgid "**-V** or **--inherit-variable NAME**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:53
msgid ""
"Snapshots the value of the variable ``NAME`` and defines a local variable "
"with that same name and value when the function is defined. This is similar "
"to a closure in other languages like Python but a bit different. Note the "
"word \"snapshot\" in the first sentence. If you change the value of the "
"variable after defining the function, even if you do so in the same scope "
"(typically another function) the new value will not be used by the function "
"you just created using this option. See the ``function notify`` example "
"below for how this might be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:55
msgid ""
"The event handler switches (``on-event``, ``on-variable``, ``on-job-exit``, "
"``on-process-exit`` and ``on-signal``) cause a function to run automatically "
"at specific events. New named events for ``--on-event`` can be fired using "
"the :doc:`emit <emit>` builtin. Fish already generates a few events, see :"
"ref:`event` for more."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:57
msgid ""
"Functions may not be named the same as a reserved keyword. These are "
"elements of fish syntax or builtin commands which are essential for the "
"operations of the shell. Current reserved words are ``[``, ``_``, ``and``, "
"``argparse``, ``begin``, ``break``, ``builtin``, ``case``, ``command``, "
"``continue``, ``else``, ``end``, ``eval``, ``exec``, ``for``, ``function``, "
"``if``, ``not``, ``or``, ``read``, ``return``, ``set``, ``status``, "
"``string``, ``switch``, ``test``, ``time``, and ``while``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:60
msgid "Example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:66
msgid ""
"function ll\n"
"    ls -l $argv\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:71
msgid ""
"will run the ``ls`` command, using the ``-l`` option, while passing on any "
"additional files and switches to ``ls``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:77
msgid ""
"function mkdir -d \"Create a directory and set CWD\"\n"
"    command mkdir $argv\n"
"    if test $status = 0\n"
"        switch $argv[(count $argv)]\n"
"            case '-*'\n"
"\n"
"            case '*'\n"
"                cd $argv[(count $argv)]\n"
"                return\n"
"        end\n"
"    end\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:91
msgid ""
"This will run the ``mkdir`` command, and if it is successful, change the "
"current working directory to the one just created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:97
msgid ""
"function notify\n"
"    set -l job (jobs -l -g)\n"
"    or begin; echo \"There are no jobs\" >&2; return 1; end\n"
"\n"
"    function _notify_job_$job --on-job-exit $job --inherit-variable job\n"
"        echo -n \\a # beep\n"
"        functions -e _notify_job_$job\n"
"    end\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:108
msgid "This will beep when the most recent job completes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:112
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/function.rst:114
msgid ""
"Events are only received from the current fish process as there is no way to "
"send events from one fish process to another."
msgstr ""

